Methodology ğŸ”¬

Data Collection: Integrated datasets covering climate (temperature, humidity, rainfall), air quality (PM2.5, PM10, CO, Oâ‚ƒ, NOâ‚‚), and epidemiological records.

Preprocessing:

Reindexed time series to continuous daily values

Handled missing values and outliers

Normalized/standardized features

Feature Engineering: Created lag features, moving averages, and climate-health interaction variables.

Model Training:

Trained baseline models using Random Forests

Applied SMOTE to resolve imbalance issues

Tuned hyperparameters via GridSearchCV

Evaluation: Assessed using accuracy, F1-score, precision-recall metrics for classification and RMSE for regression.

Results ğŸ“ˆ

Improved classification performance by handling imbalance with SMOTE.

Random Forest models provided robust performance across both classification and regression tasks.

Demonstrated potential for real-time disease outbreak risk monitoring using AI + IoT pipelines.

ğŸ‘‰ Future scope: Integration with IoT devices for real-time environmental data collection and deployment as a web-based dashboard for public health officials.
